<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Where Modal fits — and where it doesn't</h2>

<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6 mb-3">Best fit</h3>

<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 my-4 space-y-1">

<li><strong>Self-hosted open-source LLMs</strong> (Llama 4, Qwen 3, DeepSeek V4, Mistral) when you want full control over fine-tuning, system prompts, or per-request routing</li>

<li><strong>Spiky workloads</strong> where traffic comes in bursts — Modal scales to zero between bursts, so you pay nothing when idle</li>

<li><strong>Batch inference</strong> (image generation, embeddings, bulk classification) where the cost model is dominated by GPU-seconds</li>

<li><strong>Agent backends</strong> where each task runs an isolated Sandbox (similar to Claude Code's execution model)</li>

<li><strong>ML training and fine-tuning</strong> — Modal supports multi-GPU training jobs at the same per-second rates</li>

</ul>

<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6 mb-3">Poor fit</h3>

<ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 my-4 space-y-1">

<li><strong>Ultra-low-latency realtime</strong> (sub-200ms p99) — cold start is 1-3s even with warm pool. Use dedicated inference providers like Groq or Cerebras instead.</li>

<li><strong>Workloads that fit cleanly into managed model APIs</strong> — if you just need GPT-5.6 or Sonnet 5, paying per-token is simpler.</li>

<li><strong>High-volume prompt-cache workloads</strong> — Modal doesn't have a prompt cache. Long-context repeated-prefix workloads (Anthropic's sweet spot) cost more here.</li>

<li><strong>Strict data residency in mainland China</strong> — Modal's infrastructure is AWS/GCP overseas; no CN region.</li>

</ul>

